Graph both lines:

center
tikzpicture[scale=0.5]
 (-1,-2) grid (6,6);
 (-1.5,0) – (6.5,0) node[right] {$x$};
 (0,-2.5) – (0,6.5) node[above] {$y$};

 in {1,2,...,6} {
 at (,-0.1) {$\x$};
 }
 in {-2,-1,1,2,...,6} {
 at (-0.1,) {$\y$};
 }

 % y = 2x - 1
 (-0.5,-2) – (3.5,6);
 at (3,5.5) {$y = 2x - 1$};

 % y = -x + 5
 (-0.5,5.5) – (6,-1);
 at (5.5,-0.5) {$y = -x + 5$};

 % Intersection
 ll[AtlasRose] (2,3) circle (5pt);
 at (2,3) {$(2, 3)$};
tikzpicture
center

The lines intersect at $(2, 3)$.

**Check:**
$$
 y = 2x - 1: \quad 3 &= 2(2) - 1 = 3 \quad \checkmark \\
 y = -x + 5: \quad 3 &= -2 + 5 = 3 \quad \checkmark
$$

The solution is $(2, 3)$.

Convert to slope-intercept form:
$$
 x + y = 4 &\Rightarrow y = -x + 4 \\
 2x - y = 2 &\Rightarrow y = 2x - 2
$$

center
tikzpicture[scale=0.5]
 (-1,-3) grid (5,5);
 (-1.5,0) – (5.5,0) node[right] {$x$};
 (0,-3.5) – (0,5.5) node[above] {$y$};

 in {1,2,...,5} {
 at (,-0.1) {$\x$};
 }
 in {-3,...,-1,1,2,...,5} {
 at (-0.1,) {$\y$};
 }

 % y = -x + 4
 (-0.5,4.5) – (5,-1);

 % y = 2x - 2
 (0,-2) – (3.5,5);

 % Intersection
 ll[AtlasRose] (2,2) circle (5pt);
 at (2,2) {$(2, 2)$};
tikzpicture
center

The solution is $(2, 2)$.

**Check:** $2 + 2 = 4$ $2(2) - 2 = 2$
